summary: ‘’Sansa will take ownership over who she is and what she stand for, Over the course of the series she’s been completely unaware...
body:
‘’Sansa will take ownership over who she is and what she stand for, Over the course of the series she’s been completely unaware of what she wants, where she wants to be, who she really is, and at the end of this season, I feel she is the most self-assured character in the show.” - Sophie Turner, September 2018

“She’s a real, true leader of Winterfell now. And that’s where we first see her – as a very protective, empowered lady in charge. It’s the first time you ever see her like that, and it’s so amazing to see her like that – kind of owning her destiny.” - Sophie Turner, July 2018

I LOVE THIS SONG!

summary: I love the little ways the Stark girls develop together, even when apart. Sansa and Arya’s arcs first begin with the girls...
body:
I love the little ways the Stark girls develop together, even when apart.

Sansa and Arya’s arcs first begin with the girls sharpening their strongest skills: Sansa starts off as a strong writer and sewer while Arya excels in maths and physical activities. 

But by the second half of the series, they begin to learn the other’s skill-sets.  Sansa becomes more physically active and takes care of economics in the Vale while Arya turns to the arts through her time with the Braavosi theater crew.

When they reunite, they may realize they aren’t so different after all…

body:
“Even a lord as stern and flinty as Alaric Stark found himself helpless before Queen Alysanne’s stubborn charm. He allowed that he would think on what she said, and raise the matter with his sons.

The longer the queen stayed, the more Lord Alaric warmed to her, and in time Alysanne came to realize that not everything that was said of him was true. He was careful with his coin, but not niggardly; he was not humorless at all, though his humor had an edge to it, sharp as a knife; his sons and daughter and the people of Winterfell seemed to love him well enough. Once the initial frost had thawed, his lordship took the queen hunting after elk and wild boar in the wolfswood, showed her the bones of a giant, and allowed her to rummage as she pleased through his modest castle library. He even deigned to approach Silverwing, though warily.”

I can’t believe Queen Alysanne’s personal motto was

“Courtesy is a Lady’s armor”

summary: As dawn broke the next day Lord Burley took Her Grace to the top of the Wall. “Here the world ends,” he told her, gesturing at...
body:
As dawn broke the next day Lord Burley took Her Grace to the top of the Wall. “Here the world ends,” he told her, gesturing at the vast green expanse of the haunted forest beyond. Burley was apologetic for the quality of the food and drink presented to the queen, and the rudeness of the accommodations at Castle Black. “We do what we can, Your Grace,” the Lord Commander explained, “but our beds are hard, our halls are cold, and our food—”

“—is nourishing,” the queen finished. “And that is all that I require. It will please me to eat as you do.”

Just GRRM practically quoting Sansa’s interactions with the Night’s Watch.

summary: I think some people are mistaken about this GRRM quote about Sansa going around because of tumblr’s messed up formatting of...
body:
I think some people are mistaken about this GRRM quote about Sansa going around because of tumblr’s messed up formatting of quote posts. The original post was merely that first quote from a 2012 interview inspired by Marx quote. The OP’s blog nothatsnotdialectical has been deactivated but there’s a reblog of it without the Sansa addition here. The Sansa part was a meta addition by blog user wavelette, also in 2013. 

Just to be clear, this isn’t anyone making up a fake post. Tumblr’s formatting is at fault that makes it appear like this on a 2017 reblog on a blog page and later in general in people’s reblogs now. 

But people need to be more careful though in reblogging things without linked sources. I’ve been trying to find said 2012 interview (which is without the following Sansa meta) and I’m not sure I’m getting the original source. A popular book blog (asoiafuniversity) reblogged it though so I’m assuming if it is legit someone knows about it.
